solutions.content:
The challenge that I faced was to know where to add the extra student. We cannot simply add a student to a class with lowest pass ratio.

Why? For eg:  consider the ratios  2/3 (0.6666) and 3/5 (0.6) 
if we add 1 student to  2/3 -> 3/4 (0.75)
or
if we add 1 student to 3/5 -> 4/6 (0.6666)

From above we see that we cannot just simply add the student to lowest ratio (3/5).

So the idea is to compute the ratio increases (if we add one student) for each class and store in maxHeap.
The top of the heap will always have the class which is the best candidate to add the new student.

**Code:**
```
class Solution {

    // T = O(mlogc)  S=O(c)   c=no. of classes   m= extra students
    public double maxAverageRatio(int[][] classes, int extraStudents) {

        double totalPassRatios = 0.0;
        // track the max new Pass Ratio (if a student is added to a class)
        // format: double[] {passRatio increase if a student is added,   pass count,   student count}
        PriorityQueue<double[]> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b) -> Double.compare(b[0], a[0]));

        for(int i=0; i< classes.length; i++) {
            // pass ratio
            double passRatio = (double) classes[i][0]/classes[i][1];
            // alternate pass ratio if a student is added
            double altPassRatio = (double) (classes[i][0]+1)/(classes[i][1]+1);

            maxHeap.add(new double[]{altPassRatio-passRatio, classes[i][0], classes[i][1]});
        }

        while(!maxHeap.isEmpty() && extraStudents > 0) {
            double[] top = maxHeap.poll();
            double passRatio = (double) (top[1]+1)/(top[2]+1);
            double altPassRatio = (double) (top[1]+2)/(top[2]+2);
            // update the maxHeap
            maxHeap.add(new double[]{altPassRatio-passRatio, top[1]+1, top[2]+1});

            extraStudents--; // decrement the extraStudents
        }

        // add all the ratios from Heap
        while(!maxHeap.isEmpty()) {            
            double[] top = maxHeap.poll();
            double passRatio = (double) (top[1])/(top[2]);
            totalPassRatios += passRatio;
        }

        return totalPassRatios / classes.length;
    }
}
```

