The **intuition** behind solving this problem is that, suppose we had to assign only one extra student to a class, then, we'll be assigning that student to such a class which will yield maximum profit.
For p (students that can pass exam) & tot (total students), profit after assigning the single student is given by:
	profit = (p+1)/(tot+1) - p/tot

Thus, for  k extra students, we can greedily assign each of the k students to a class which will give max profit.

Max Heap can be used, so that we can extract  the required max profit in O(1) ;

***
	double maxAverageRatio(vector<vector<int>>& classes, int extraStudents) {
        priority_queue <pair <double  ,pair<int,int>>> pq;  //max heap which stores profit
		int p,tot;
        double profit,sum=0;

        for(auto x:classes) {
            p=x[0];
            tot=x[1];
            profit =  (double)(p+1)/(tot+1) - (double)p/tot;
            pq.push( {profit, {p,tot}});
        }

        while(extraStudents--) {
            auto tmp = pq.top();
            auto tmp2 = tmp.second;
            p = tmp2.first;
            tot = tmp2.second;
			pq.pop();

			// add one extra student to class and push it back into heap with expected profit
            p+=1;
            tot+=1;
			profit =  (double)(p+1)/(tot+1) - (double)p/tot;
            pq.push( {profit, {p,tot}});
        }

		// adding the pass ratio of all the classes with newly assigned students
        while(!pq.empty()) {
            auto tmp = pq.top();
            auto tmp2 = tmp.second;
            p = tmp2.first;
            tot = tmp2.second;
			pq.pop();

            sum += (double)p/tot;
        }

		// average of all pass ratio
        return (double)sum/(classes.size());

    }
***

Please note that, we haven't actually assigned one student while pushing in heap. Here. everytime we push the profit into heap, we are actually pushing the expected profit after adding one student along with current p & tot.
And when we pop the class with max profit, then we finally add one student to that class.

**Complexity Analysis:**
Time : 
O( m logn + n logn) => O(m logn)  ... b'coz m & n are of same order
 *where m is extraStudents & n is no of classes*

 Space :
 O(n)  ... *only used for storing classes*.

