The minute the contest is over, I realized the solution was so simple. Wasted the whole time working on a totally wrong path. Sad.
**Key points:**
* Calculate ratio gain for inserting a student to each class. Use that ratio gain as key in a priority queue. Bundle class id in the queue with ratio gain.
* Each time, insert a student into the highest ratio gain class. Recalculate that class's ratio gain after and maintain the queue. Repeat until all good students are inserted.
* Do the ratio average calculation at the end.
```
    double maxAverageRatio(vector<vector<int>>& classes, int extraStudents) {
      std::priority_queue<std::pair<double, int>> q;
      for (int i=0; i<classes.size(); ++i)
        q.push({(classes[i][0]+1.0)/(classes[i][1]+1.0) - double(classes[i][0])/double(classes[i][1]), i});
      for (int i=0; i<extraStudents; ++i) {
        auto p = q.top();
        q.pop();
        ++classes[p.second][0];
        ++classes[p.second][1];
        q.push({(classes[p.second][0]+1.0)/(classes[p.second][1]+1.0) - double(classes[p.second][0])/double(classes[p.second][1]), p.second});
      }
      double ratios = 0;
      for (int i=0; i<classes.size(); ++i)
        ratios += double(classes[i][0])/double(classes[i][1]);
      return ratios/classes.size();
    }
