**Q & A:**
Q1: How does method 1 guarantee that k will be bounded by low & high? for the Java code (1st implementation) of method1, low could be already greater than k and you are still updating the score value. for the Python 3 code (2nd implementation) of method1, both low and high could pass the k index.
A1: In both java and Python 3 codes of method 1, there is no way that low and high bounds (`lo` & `hi`) pass index `k`. They can at most reach index `k`.
1. If they reach index `k` at the same time (e.g., test case: `nums = [1], k = 0`), then the `while` loop will terminate;
2. If `lo` reaches index `k` first, `runningMinFromIndexK[lo]` is now the max value - `runningMinFromIndexK[k]`. Then in the following iterations, `runningMinFromIndexK[lo] < runningMinFromIndexK[hi]` will always be `false` and the code can only execute `--hi` part till `lo == hi`. Accordingly, the `while` loop will termianate; Vice versa for the case of `hi` reaching index `k` first.

In fact, in the following if conditional
```
            if (hi == k || runningMinFromIndexK[lo] < runningMinFromIndexK[hi]) {
```
`hi == k` is redundant and has been removed.

**End of Q & A**

----

**Method 1:**
Similar problem: [42. Trapping Rain Water](https://leetcode.com/problems/trapping-rain-water/)

----

1. Scan starting from index `k`, to left and right, respectively, to compute running minimum values and save it in  `runningMinFromIndexK`;
 Define left running minimum to the left of `nums[k]` and right running minimum to the right of `nums[k]` by `running_left` and `running_right`, respectively. For example for `nums = [1,4,3,7,4,5]` and `k = 2` we have:
 ```
 running_left = [1,3,3,7], running_right = [7, 4, 4].
 ```
 Remove a duplicate `7` and combine the above, we have:
 ```
runningMinFromIndexK = [1,3,3,7,4,4]
```
2. Using the approach for [42. Trapping Rain Water](https://leetcode.com/problems/trapping-rain-water/): Starting from both ends as the first good subarray, move the end corresponds to smaller value of the `runningMinFromIndexK`, and update the score accordingly.
```java
    public int maximumScore(int[] nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.length, score = nums[k], lo = 0, hi = n - 1;
        int[] runningMinFromIndexK = new int[n];
        runningMinFromIndexK[k] = nums[k];
        for (int i = k + 1; i < n; ++i) { // running minimum to the right part.
            runningMinFromIndexK[i] = Math.min(runningMinFromIndexK[i - 1], nums[i]);
        }
        for (int i = k - 1; i >= 0; --i) { // running minimum to the left part.
            runningMinFromIndexK[i] = Math.min(runningMinFromIndexK[i + 1], nums[i]);
        } 
        while (lo < hi) { // This part similar to the approach for 84. Largest Rectange Histogram.
            score = Math.max(score, (hi - lo + 1) * Math.min(runningMinFromIndexK[lo], runningMinFromIndexK[hi]));
            if (runningMinFromIndexK[lo] < runningMinFromIndexK[hi]) {
                ++lo;
            }else {
                --hi;
            }
        }
        return score;
    }
```
```python
    def maximumScore(self, nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:
        running_left = list(accumulate(nums[: k + 1][:: -1], min))[:: -1]
        running_right = list(accumulate(nums[k :], min))
        running_min_from_index_k = running_left[: -1] + running_right
        n = len(nums)
        lo, hi, score = 0, n - 1, nums[k]
        while lo < hi:
            if running_min_from_index_k[lo] < running_min_from_index_k[hi]:
                score = max(score, running_min_from_index_k[lo] * (hi - lo + 1))
                lo += 1
            else:
                score = max(score, running_min_from_index_k[hi] * (hi - lo + 1))
                hi -= 1
        return score
```
**Analysis:**

Time & space: `O(n)`, where n = nums.length.

