                left--;
                minVal = min(minVal, nums[left]);
            }

            res = max(res, minVal * (right - left + 1));
        }

        return res;
    }
};
```

solutions.content:
*Always think of brute force solution first, then start working on how to optimise.*

**Idea:**
In this problem we have a pivot at index `k`, that gives the idea of treating both the splits of array differently. 
Using this intuition you can come up with using two-pointer approach.

**Solution:**
To find the maximum score of subarray having largest minimum element around index `k`, element at index `k` will always be included in the solution, so initialize the `left` and `right` pointer at `k`. 
(Initially our possible array is of length 1, including nums[k], whick is our initial minimum value)
Now include the minimum of next left and next right pointer (that is, minimum of `l_val` and`r_val`) in our solution at the same time increment/decrement the corresponding pointer after recalculating the minimum value of our current array.
We need to keep in mind that our loop will not give correct answer if good subarray is of length `n` because we have set the condition statement so that it will exit the loop once both the pointers have exceded the possible index value, to get through this we need to consider this once loop ends as we have already calculated the minimum value for entire array now.

**Code:**
```
int maximumScore(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
	int n=nums.size(),mx_score=0;
	int left=k,right=k,mn_value=nums[k];
	while(left>=0 || right<n){
		mx_score=max(mx_score,mn*(right-left-1));
		int l_val=(left==-1?INT_MIN:nums[left]);
		int r_val=(j==n?INT_MIN:nums[right]);
		if(l_val>=r_val)
			mn_value=min(mn_value,nums[left--]);
		else mn_value=min(mn_value,nums[right++]);
	}
	mx_score=max(mx_score,mn_value*n);
	return mx;
}
```
**Complexity:**
Time complexity=O(n), single iteration over entire length.
Space complexity=O(1)

