# Approach
Start with left and right pointers both set to the initial index (k) and expand in both directions: 

* "skim over" indices with higher or equal scores than the current minimum since those scores have no effect. 
* Once you reach "edges" on both sides (beyond those points are lower scores) - Calculate the score between the pointers and update the maximum if the score is higher than the existing one.
* Set current minimum as max(nums[left], nums[right]) and continue until the array is fully analyzed.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int maximumScore(int[] nums, int k) {
        int max = 0;
        int left = k;
        int right = k;
        int currElevation = nums[k];
        while (left >= 0 || right < nums.length) {
            while (left >= 0 && nums[left] >= currElevation) {
                left--;
            }
            while (right < nums.length && nums[right] >= currElevation) {
                right++;
            }
            max = Math.max(max, currElevation * (right - left - 1));
            if (left >= 0 && right < nums.length) {
                currElevation = Math.max(nums[left], nums[right]);
            } else if (left >= 0) {
                currElevation = nums[left];
            } else if (right < nums.length){
                currElevation = nums[right];
            }
        }
        return max;
    }
}
```

