# Intuition
Since it requires finding the minimum element in a subarray, we need to use monotonic stack to find the previous and next minimum elements.

# Approach
This is very similar to the Sum of Subarray Minimums and we use a monotonically increasing stack to find the subarray where a specific element will be the minimum. We want to find the largest such subarray. If the subarray bounds satisfy the condition of `i <= k <= j`, we update our result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
- Space complexity: O(n)

# Code
```
func maximumScore(nums []int, k int) int {
  var stack []int
  stack = append(stack, -1) // for convenience
  var res int
  // Just use a monotonic stack to find the previous minimum and next minimum index
  // we can use the top of the stack as the minimum element.
  for idx := 0; idx <= len(nums); idx++ {
    for len(stack) > 1 && (idx == len(nums) || nums[stack[len(stack)-1]] > nums[idx]) {
      min := nums[stack[len(stack)-1]]
      stack = stack[:len(stack)-1]
      // i and j are the boundaries of the sub array where top of the stack is the
      // minimum element.
      i, j := stack[len(stack)-1] + 1, idx - 1
      if i <= k && k <= j {
        res = max(res, min * (j - i + 1))
      }
    }
    stack = append(stack, idx)
  }
  return res
}

func max(a, b int) int {
  if a > b {
    return a
  }
  return b
}
```

