# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This problem is silimar to Largest Area in a Histogram. What makes it simpler is the fact that we have been given where to begin (`at k`). As a result we don't have to use stacks (Recall we needed stack to keep a track of previous minimum for a particular index assuming rectangle can be pivoted at any index. Here we've been given the pivot `k`).
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Start `i` from `k-1` and go to `0`. We will keep a track of current minimum number encountered. Keep on modifying `nums[i]` with that minimum. (Notice that higher values of `nums[i]` won't be involved in the answer anyways).
2. Start `i` from `k+1` again and to `n-1` (`n == nums.size()`). Do the same as above.
3. Notice as `i` goes from `k-1` to `0`, the numbers we encounter that are higher than current minimum won't ever become a minimum in a valid subarray as `i<=k` (For them to become minimum, `j` has to be less than `k`). This same is true for when `i` goes from `k+1` to `n-1`.
4. Now do a typical two-pointer greedy approach to find the `maxscore` starting from `i=0` and `j=n-1`. Reduce that pointer which contains the minimum of `nums[i]` and `nums[j]` and at every iteration keep on finding the `maxscore`.

Do Upvote if you liked the SOlution :)
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
`O(n)` As we have only traversed linearly
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
`O(1)` We were smart enough to do it in place ;)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumScore(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int minval = nums[k];
        int n = nums.size();
        for (int i=k-1;i>=0;i--){
            minval = min(minval,nums[i]);
            nums[i] = minval;
        }
        minval = nums[k];
        for (int j=k+1;j<n;j++){
            minval = min(minval,nums[j]);
            nums[j] = minval;
        }
        //for (auto i:v) cout<<i<<" ";
        int i=0,j=n-1;
        int maxscore = -1;
        while (i <= j){
            int score = (j-i+1)*min(nums[i],nums[j]);
            maxscore = max(maxscore,score);
            if (nums[i] < nums[j]) i++;
            else j--;
        }
        return maxscore;
    }
};
```

